Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Zend/zend_builtin_functions.c\n+++ b/Zend/zend_builtin_functions.c\n@@ -1736,6 +1736,10 @@\n \t\t} else if (UNEXPECTED((ZEND_CALL_INFO(call) & ZEND_CALL_GENERATOR) != 0)) {\n \t\t\tprev = zend_generator_check_placeholder_frame(prev);\n+\t\t\tif (!prev || !prev->func) {\n+\t\t\t\tcall = prev;\n+\t\t\t\tcontinue;\n+\t\t\t}\n \t\t}\n'}`
responded: From the evidence, the segfault occurs at `prev->func->common.type`, even after all previous pointer checks. This means that `prev->func` can point to already-freed memory, which a NULL check cannot catch.

There is only one reliable approach in C to prevent such use-after-free/dangling pointer dereference: **after a generator check, re-validate all pointers**. The code performs:
```c
if (UNEXPECTED((ZEND_CALL_INFO(call) & ZEND_CALL_GENERATOR) != 0)) {
    prev = zend_generator_check_placeholder_frame(prev);
}
```
If `zend_generator_check_placeholder_frame(prev)` returns a dangling pointer, all following dereferences are unsafe.

**New Plan:**
- After the generator check, re-check `prev` and `prev->func` for NULL before dereferencing any field.

### Patch
Insert a check right after the generator check:
```diff
@@ -1736,6 +1736,10 @@
         } else if (UNEXPECTED((ZEND_CALL_INFO(call) & ZEND_CALL_GENERATOR) != 0)) {
             prev = zend_generator_check_placeholder_frame(prev);
+            if (!prev || !prev->func) {
+                call = prev;
+                continue;
+            }
         }
```
This ensures that if the generator check returns NULL or an invalid frame, it will skip before any field access.

Let's apply and validate this patch.

