responded: The crucial bug is that the check:
```c
if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type))
```
**does NOT check if prev->opline is non-NULL before using it.**

Currently, the code will still execute `prev->opline->opcode` when `prev->opline` may be NULL.

**The fix MUST move `prev->opline` null-check to the conditional:**  
So, instead of:
```c
if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type)) {
    // use prev->opline->...
}
```
We should do:
```c
if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type) && prev->opline) {
   // safe to use prev->opline->opcode and prev->opline->lineno
...
} else if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type)) {
   // fallback when prev->opline is NULL (only)
...
}
```
This prevents *any* access to `prev->opline->opcode` or `prev->opline->lineno` unless it is non-null.

We should apply this split logic in BOTH places the code does the dereference.

Let's make that precise patch.

